Serge Oulon, Adama Bayala, and Kalifara Séré are journalists from Burkina Faso who faced threats and violence due to their reporting on corruption, conflict, and human rights abuses. In regions with political instability, journalists risk surveillance, harassment, and even physical harm for exposing the truth.

Protecting data and communications is crucial to keep sources safe and avoid government or militant monitoring. Offline, encrypted messaging tools help prevent interception, reduce tracking, and safeguard sensitive information. Key ideas to explore include press freedom, digital privacy, encrypted communication, offline security, and protection of journalists.